ire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lettice","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English, Old French female personal name  <i>Letice</i> (from Latin  <i>laetitia</i> ‘joy’).  See also  Leece  ,   Leeson  ,   Lett  , and   Letson  .","2  Scottish:  see  Letters   (1)."],"variants":[{"name":"Leece","meanings":["English: from a medieval female personal name, <i>Lece</i>, a short form of <i>Lettice</i> (from Latin <i>Laetitia</i>, meaning ‘happiness, gaiety’).","English: variant of   Lees  .","Irish: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Íosa</i>, Manx <i>Mac Guilley Yeesey</i> ‘son of <i>Giolla Íosa</i> (devotee or servant of Jesus)’. Ballaleece (‘Leece's farm’) in Kirk German was the family's main seat."]},{"name":"Letson","meanings":["English and Scottish: metronymic from   Lett  ."]},{"name":"Latus","meanings":["Polish (<b>Latuś</b>): from a derivative of <i>lato</i> ‘summer’ (see   Lato  ).","English: nickname from Middle English <i>latewys</i>, apparently a compound of <i>late</i> + <i>wise</i> ‘lately wise’ or ‘belatedly wise; wise after the event’. The surname has been shortened to <i>Latus</i> and through folk etymology re-interpreted as <i>Lat(e)house</i>. It may also have been confused with   Letts  ."]},{"name":"Letters","meanings":["Scottish: locative name from Letters (Ross and Cromarty), Leitters (Perths), or any of many other minor places in Scotland named with Gaelic  <i>leiter</i> ‘steep slope’."]},{"name":"Leeson","meanings":["English (mainly Northamptonshire): metronymic from   Leece  1."]},{"name":"Lett","meanings":["English: from a short form of the medieval female personal name <i>Lettice</i> (see   Leece   1).","German: from Middle High German <i>lette</i> ‘clay, clayey soil’, hence a topographic name for someone who farmed on fertile clay soil.","Chinese: possibly from Cantonese form of the Chinese name 力 (meaning ‘power, strength’), a monosyllabic personal name, or part of a disyllabic personal name of some early Chinese immigrants in the US."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Lettice was born about 1465, in Dymock, Gloucestershire, England, her father, John Lettice, was 26 and her mother, Ann Smith, was 21. She had at least 1 son with William Daniel Hankins. She died in 1500, in her hometown, at the age of 36."},"et":{"about 1465–1500":"umbes 1465–1500","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1500–1538":"1500–1538","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","1450":"1450","abt 1500":"umbes 1500","1512":"1512","1500":"1500","1445":"1445","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","about 1465":"umbes 1465","after 1464":"pärast 1464","1538":"1538","about 1494":"umbes 1494","England ":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1465–1500":"noin 1465–1500","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1500–1538":"1500–1538","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1445–1494":"1445–1494","1440":"1440","1494":"1494","1450":"1450","abt 1500":"noin 1500","1512":"1512","1500":"1500","1445":"1445","1465":"1465","1464":"1464","about 1465":"noin 1465","after 1464":"1464 jälkeen","1538":"1538","about 1494":"noin 1494","England ":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Essex, England":"Essex, England","Dymock, Gloucestershire, England":"Dymock, Gloucestershire, England"},"fr":{"about 1465–1500":"environ 1465–1500","1465–1500":"1465–1500","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1500–1538":"1500–1538","1440–1464":"1440–1464","1445–1494